# Vue: Extract Reusable Components

When the same UI pattern, markup structure, or behaviour appears in more than one place, extract it into a shared component in `src/components/` rather than duplicating it. Duplication means bug fixes and style changes must be applied in multiple places and often drift out of sync.

**Signals that extraction is warranted:**
- The same block of template markup appears in two or more views/components
- The same combination of props, state, and event handlers is set up repeatedly
- A raw HTML element is used with the same set of classes or attributes in multiple places, where a shared component already exists that wraps that element (e.g. use `<BaseButton>` instead of `<button>`, use `<InputField>` instead of `<input>`)
- The same `try/catch` + toast + loading-flag pattern is repeated across multiple handlers

**When extracting a component:**
- Place it in `src/components/` with a descriptive PascalCase name
- Accept data via props and emit events for actions — do not couple it to a specific view's state
- Prefer a single-responsibility component over a large multi-purpose one

**Wrong — duplicating a loading button pattern across views:**
```html
<!-- In SkillsView.vue -->
<button :disabled="loading" @click="sync">
  <span v-if="loading">Syncing…</span>
  <span v-else>Sync</span>
</button>

<!-- In RulesView.vue — identical markup -->
<button :disabled="loading" @click="sync">
  <span v-if="loading">Syncing…</span>
  <span v-else>Sync</span>
</button>
```

**Right — use the existing BaseButton with its loading prop:**
```html
<BaseButton :loading="loading" @click="sync">Sync</BaseButton>
```

Before writing new template markup, check `src/components/` for an existing component that covers the use case.
